align:874f3728-80f5-49b1-a122-eed971848b9d a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:3ccc1e44-1f86-4ca1-99ca-80678ed7c582 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts relate to the process of 'Validation', however AIDOC specifically focuses on validation *within* AI/ML model development using datasets, while mex-core's 'Validation' appears more general and lacks this specific context in its provided description. They are highly related and could be used interchangeably in many contexts concerning data quality assessment, but the AI focus of AIDOC introduces a nuance."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:DataValidation ;
    align:target <http://mex.aksw.org/mex-core#Validation> .

align:cc8a11ac-7ade-4c96-b411-989e29b0a98c a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:3ccc1e44-1f86-4ca1-99ca-80678ed7c582 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts refer to the process of 'Training' within an AI/data context. The AIDOC definition explicitly mentions *datasets* and *model training*, while mex-core’s description is missing (and therefore less specific). While not identical due to the lack of detail in `mex-core`, they are highly related and likely interchangeable in many contexts."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:DataTraining ;
    align:target <http://mex.aksw.org/mex-core#Training> .

align:d2b204c2-40f2-4b24-b78a-0fbbe83aa6d4 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:3ccc1e44-1f86-4ca1-99ca-80678ed7c582 ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts refer to a computational representation used for tasks. The AIDOC definition explicitly links it to 'AI methods' and 'AI tasks', while the mex-core concept is more general ('Model'). They are highly similar but not identical; an AI Model *is* a Model, but not all Models are necessarily AI Models."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AIModel ;
    align:target <http://mex.aksw.org/mex-core#Model> .

align:ddd31aef-0710-44ca-aa64-ba24f54f6453 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:3ccc1e44-1f86-4ca1-99ca-80678ed7c582 ;
    align:confidence "0.95"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "The AIDOC concept explicitly states it *is derived from* prov:Activity (which is what mex-core's Activity uses as its URI). The descriptions are highly aligned – both represent an 'activity'. While AIDOC specifies this activity relates to the AI lifecycle, that doesn’t fundamentally change the underlying meaning of ‘activity’ itself. Therefore, they can be considered interchangeable in many contexts."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:exactMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AIActivity ;
    align:target <http://www.w3.org/ns/prov-o#Activity> .

